Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Lawrence OTIENO¶

Introduction¶

The dataset provided contains 113,937 rows and 81 columns that depict loan borrowing, including loan amount, borrower rate, loan status etc. This data will be cleaned and analyzed visually to generate insights.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Data Wrangling process done for exploratory data analysis.

# Rename ListingCategory
loan_df.rename(columns={'ListingCategory (numeric)':'ListingCategory'}, inplace=True)

# Change ListingCategory from integers to actual words for easy observation
listingCat = {0:'Not Available',1:'Debt Consolidation',2:'Home Improvement',3:'Business',4:'Personal Loan',5:'Student Use',6:'Auto',
                7:'Other',8:'Baby&Adoption',9:'Boat',10:'Cosmetic Procedure',11:'Engagement Ring',12:'Green Loans',13:'Household Expenses',
                14:'Large Purchases',15:'Medical/Dental',16:'Motorcycle',17:'RV',18:'Taxes',19:'Vacation',20:'Wedding Loans'}

# Function to loop through the list above for changing
def entire_list(i):
    if i in listingCat.keys():
        return listingCat[i]
    else:
        return i
               
# Apply function to ListingCategory
loan_df['ListingCategory'] = loan_df['ListingCategory'].apply(lambda x: entire_list(x))

# Check if the function worked
loan_df['ListingCategory'].unique()

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Before Cleaning: There were 78754 entries in the dataset with 81 columns.

After Cleaning: There are 57298 entries in the dataset with 14 columns.

The dataset have Variables of different datatypes.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • Factors determining amount of loans given.
  • Effects of employment status and income range on amount of loans given.
  • Sates with high number of people taking loans.
  • Profits and risks involve in giving loans.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Term
  • LoanStatus
  • BorrowerAPR
  • BorrowerRate
  • LenderYield
  • ProsperScore
  • ListingCategory
  • BorrowerState
  • Occupation
  • EmploymentStatus
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner
  • IncomeRange
  • LoanOriginalAmount

Univariate Exploration¶

Investigation of distributions of individual variables taking into consideration the relationships between variables.

What is the distribution of LoanStatus?¶

In [22]:
# Set figure size and colour
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (16, 8))
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

# Arrange in descending order
order_sort = loan_df['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index

# Bar chart for LoanStatus
sb.countplot(data=loan_df, x='LoanStatus' , ax=ax, color=base_color, order=order_sort)
plt.title('Bar Chart for Loan Status')
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
plt.ylabel('Number of Loans')
plt.xticks(rotation = 90)

# Prin values on bars
freq = loan_df.LoanStatus.value_counts()
for i in range(len(freq)):
    count = freq[i]
    plt.text(i,count,count, ha='center', va='bottom');
    
plt.show;

Observation(s)¶

  • Most of the loans in the dataset are current which is 37761 as shown on plot above.
  • Significant number of loans are either completed or chargedoff.
  • A number of loans have been defaulted and past due dates, which is a bad trend to the organization.

What is the distribution of ProsperScore?¶

ProsperScore is a custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score.

In [24]:

Observation(s)¶

  • The ProsperScore (as seen in the plot above) shows the most count at 4.0, 6.0 and 8.0 meaning that loans were taken by people with medium-risk score.

Conclusions¶

  • Most loans were taken for debt consolidation.
  • Loans with high lender yield have high risk.
  • People with high income range or employed get more loans.
  • Loans that have gone past due dates (>120 days) risk not getting paid.
  • Most borrowers come from California (CA), New York (NY) and Texas (TX) respectively.
